ace <i>c.</i> 1160. The Scottish surname is also common in Ulster.","Irish: variant of   McCutcheon   from <b>Mac Uisdein</b> or <b>Mac Uistein</b>.","History: In 1836 the newly founded city of Houston, TX, was named in honor of Sam Houston (1793–1863), soldier and statesman. As commander in chief of the Texan army he achieved Texas independence from Mexico by routing the army of the Mexican general Santa Anna. His ancestors were Ulster Scots who had emigrated to Philadelphia, PA, in the 18th century."]}]},{"name":"Finlay","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Scottish Gaelic name Fionnlagh  or a transferred use of the surname derived from the given name. This is one of a set of Celtic names which in recent years has also been favoured increasingly among parents without Scottish connections. It is also used occasionally for girls."],"variants":[{"name":"Findlay","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Finlay ."]},{"name":"Fionnlagh","meanings":["Traditional: from Gaelic <i>fionn</i> ‘white, fair’ + <i>laogh</i> ‘warrior, hero’, reinforced apparently by an Old Norse personal name composed of <i>finn</i> ‘Finn’ + <i>leikr</i> ‘battle; hero’."]},{"name":"Finley","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Scottish Gaelic name Fionnlagh  or a transferred use of the surname derived from the given name. This is one of a set of Celtic names which in recent years has also been favoured increasingly among parents without Scottish connections. It is also used occasionally for girls."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Finlay de Houstoun was born in 1250, in Houston, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Simon de Houston. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1296, in Killearn, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1250–1296":"1250–1296","1276–1350":"1276–1350","1239–1296":"1239–1296","1239":"1239","1276":"1276","1296":"1296","1350":"1350","1250":"125